R Library CausalImpact on Inferring Causal Relationships

install.packages("CausalImpact")
Error in install.packages : Updating loaded packages

1. Linear Simulated Data

set.seed(1)
x1 <- 100 + arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.999), n = 1000)
x2 <- 50 + arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.8), n=1000) 
x3 <- 20 + arima.sim(model = list(ma=0.7), n =1000)
y <- 0.01*x1 + 0.3*x2 + 0.01 * x3 +rnorm(1000)
x1_range <- x1[701:1000]
y[701:1000] <- y[701:1000] + 0.05*x1_range + 5
data <- cbind(y, x1, x2, x3)
plot.ts(data)

NA
NA
pre.period <- c(1, 700)
post.period <- c(701, 1000)
impact <- CausalImpact(data, pre.period, post.period)

plot(impact)

summary(impact)

For more details, type: summary(impact, "report")
summary(impact, "report")
Analysis report {CausalImpact}


During the post-intervention period, the response variable had an average value of approx. 25.84. By contrast, in the absence of an intervention, we would have expected an average response of 16.10. The 95% interval of this counterfactual prediction is [15.78, 16.43]. Subtracting this prediction from the observed response yields an estimate of the causal effect the intervention had on the response variable. This effect is 9.74 with a 95% interval of [9.41, 10.06]. For a discussion of the significance of this effect, see below.

Summing up the individual data points during the post-intervention period (which can only sometimes be meaningfully interpreted), the response variable had an overall value of 7.75K. By contrast, had the intervention not taken place, we would have expected a sum of 4.83K. The 95% interval of this prediction is [4.73K, 4.93K].

The above results are given in terms of absolute numbers. In relative terms, the response variable showed an increase of +61%. The 95% interval of this percentage is [+58%, +62%].

This means that the positive effect observed during the intervention period is statistically significant and unlikely to be due to random fluctuations. It should be noted, however, that the question of whether this increase also bears substantive significance can only be answered by comparing the absolute effect (9.74) to the original goal of the underlying intervention.

The probability of obtaining this effect by chance is very small (Bayesian one-sided tail-area probability p = 0.001). This means the causal effect can be considered statistically significant.

2. Nonlinear Simulated Data

x1 <- 100 + arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.999), n = 1000)
x2 <- 50 + arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.8), n=1000) 
x3 <- 20 + arima.sim(model = list(ma=0.7), n =1000)
y <- 0.1*(x1^2) + 0.03*(x2^3) + 0.01 * x3 +rnorm(1000)
x1_range <- x1[701:1000]
y[701:1000] <- y[701:1000] + 0.03*(x1_range^2) + 5
nonlineardata <- cbind(y, x1, x2, x3)
plot.ts(nonlineardata)


pre.period <- c(1, 700)
post.period <- c(701, 1000)
impact <- CausalImpact(nonlineardata, pre.period, post.period)

plot(impact)

summary(impact)

3. Observational Dataset: Policy Intervention by Central Bank # reference: https://nzlul.medium.com/causalimpact-analysis-using-r-4d9d4fdeb2d7

setwd("/Users/ece/Downloads")
The working directory was changed to /Users/ece/Downloads inside a notebook chunk. The working directory will be reset when the chunk is finished running. Use the knitr root.dir option in the setup chunk to change the working directory for notebook chunks.
df <- read.csv("CausalExercise.csv")
install.packages("psych")
library(psych)
describe(df)
# Reference: https://nzlul.medium.com/causalimpact-analysis-using-r-4d9d4fdeb2d7
time.points <- seq.Date(as.Date("2020-02-27"), by = 1, length.out = 44)
ibcl <- ts(df$IBCL)
u10yr <- ts(df$VIX)
vix <- ts(df$VIX)
#Bind the data
data <- zoo(cbind(ibcl,u10yr,vix), time.points)
head(data)
             ibcl u10yr   vix
2020-02-27 3.8125 39.16 39.16
2020-02-28 3.7188 40.11 40.11
2020-02-29 3.7813 33.42 33.42
2020-03-01 3.7813 36.82 36.82
2020-03-02 3.8125 31.99 31.99
2020-03-03 3.7188 39.62 39.62
pre.period <- as.Date(c("2020-02-27","2020-03-23"))
post.period <- as.Date(c("2020-03-24","2020-04-10"))
# default CausalImpact object initiated
impact <- CausalImpact(data, pre.period, post.period)
plot(impact)

summary(impact)

summary(impact, "report")
Analysis report {CausalImpact}


During the post-intervention period, the response variable had an average value of approx. 3.07. By contrast, in the absence of an intervention, we would have expected an average response of 3.67. The 95% interval of this counterfactual prediction is [3.58, 3.75]. Subtracting this prediction from the observed response yields an estimate of the causal effect the intervention had on the response variable. This effect is -0.59 with a 95% interval of [-0.68, -0.51]. For a discussion of the significance of this effect, see below.

Summing up the individual data points during the post-intervention period (which can only sometimes be meaningfully interpreted), the response variable had an overall value of 55.27. By contrast, had the intervention not taken place, we would have expected a sum of 65.97. The 95% interval of this prediction is [64.39, 67.50].

The above results are given in terms of absolute numbers. In relative terms, the response variable showed a decrease of -16%. The 95% interval of this percentage is [-19%, -14%].

This means that the negative effect observed during the intervention period is statistically significant. If the experimenter had expected a positive effect, it is recommended to double-check whether anomalies in the control variables may have caused an overly optimistic expectation of what should have happened in the response variable in the absence of the intervention.

The probability of obtaining this effect by chance is very small (Bayesian one-sided tail-area probability p = 0.001). This means the causal effect can be considered statistically significant.
